BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kzy3UTdEswrc4vDzi-y0G
SUMMARY:Design and Evaluation of Ruthenium-Based Anode Catalyst for Acidic 
	Oxygen Evolution in Proton-Exchange Membrane Water Electrolysis
DTSTAMP:20260616T175128Z
DTSTART:20260618T153000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Chang Qiu  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis Defense
	  Department: Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering  Location: Ralph O'Con
	nor Building 306  Proton-exchange membrane (PEM) water electrolysis is a p
	romising technology for sustainable hydrogen production\, but its large-sc
	ale deployment is limited by the scarcity and high cost of iridium (Ir) -b
	ased anode catalysts. Ruthenium oxide (RuO2) exhibits high intrinsic activ
	ity for the acidic oxygen evolution reaction (OER)\, yet its poor stabilit
	y under oxidizing acidic conditions remains a major challenge. This disser
	tation focuses on the design and evaluation of ruthenium (Ru)-based anode 
	catalyst for durable acidic OER in PEM water electrolysis.  &#160\;  First
	\, a low-Ir stabilized RuO2 catalyst is developed to reduce iridium usage 
	while maintaining high activity and durability in a practical PEM electrol
	yzer. Second\, ruthenium–lead oxide catalysts are investigated as an alter
	native strategy for improving acidic OER activity. Third\, the relationshi
	p between crystallinity and electrocatalytic stability is examined using p
	ure RuO₂ catalysts\, revealing the importance of structural order in deter
	mining catalyst durability. Finally\, the interpretation of electrochemica
	l performance is revisited by analyzing hidden biases in RHE-based potenti
	al conversion under local pH gradients.  Together\, these studies provide 
	insights into composition engineering\, structural stability\, and electro
	chemical evaluation of Ru-based acidic OER catalysts. The findings contrib
	ute to the rational development of durable and low cost anode catalysts fo
	r PEM water electrolysis.  (Department : Chemical and Biomolecular Enginee
	ring)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/events/430289-design-and-evaluation-
	of-ruthenium-based-anode\n\nFrom Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/430289-design-and-evaluation-of-rut
	henium-based-anode
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Ralph O'Connor Building
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:6D5IDEaWQlQfn-gwyOsaS
SUMMARY:Stochastic Simulations of Radiation Belt Relativistic Wave-Particle
	 Interactions
DTSTAMP:20260616T175128Z
DTSTART:20260618T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Suhail Aldhurais  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis 
	Defense  Department: Applied Physics  Location: Herman Brown Hall 227  Rad
	ial diffusion has been considered a primary transport and energization mec
	hanism in Earth's radiation belts since soon after its discovery in 1958. 
	Although its validity remains an open question\, it is incorporated into m
	any radiation belt models. Radiation belt particles are characterized by t
	hree periodic motions—gyro\, bounce\, and drift—each associated with an ad
	iabatic invariant. Radial diffusion requires violating the drift invariant
	 via ultra low-frequency (ULF) wave-particle interactions (WPIs). This the
	sis investigates relativistic guiding-center ULF-WPIs in Earth's equatoria
	l dipole field through complementary numerical simulations and theoretical
	 derivations. Both electric (derivable from a scalar potential) and electr
	omagnetic (derivable from a vector potential) WPIs are considered. First\,
	 deterministic single-mode ULF-WPIs are analyzed using Poincaré plots whos
	e numerical island half-widths agree with theory. Then\, diffusive WPIs ar
	e simulated\, and resulting numerical diffusion coefficients agree with th
	eory. We also consider perturbations similar to those described in Fältham
	mar (1965)\, a foundational work on the topic. While agreement is obtained
	 for the electric part\, a discrepancy is found for the electromagnetic pa
	rt due to an assumption made in his work and when modified\, agreement is 
	achieved. Next\, multimode ULF-WPIs are examined. First\, the wave perturb
	ations are analyzed and the "effective correlation" is developed. Then\, w
	e explore three wave parameters: The spectrum frequency width\, spacing\, 
	and amplitude. We find that the decorrelation time of the system is invers
	ely proportional to the spectrum width. A wide spectrum width\, a narrow s
	pectrum spacing\, and an intermediate amplitude are required to achieve a 
	quasilinear diffusive interaction. Poincaré island overlap ratios are simu
	ltaneously tracked to determine lower and upper bounds of the quasilinear 
	diffusive region.  Radiation belt dynamics include other WPIs spanning tim
	escales from milliseconds to minutes\, complicating their incorporation in
	 a single simulation using conventional methods. We present results from a
	 separate computational model\, K2\, simulating the March 17\, 2013 geomag
	netic event. The model combines a magnetohydrodynamic (MHD)-particle frame
	work (incorporating ULF processes) with stochastic differential equation (
	SDE) methods that incorporate chorus wave processes. Furthermore\, nonline
	ar effects (e.g.\, phase trapping and bunching) are also incorporated in K
	2\, and the results are interpolated along spacecraft trajectories where s
	ignificant under-sampling arises.  &#160\;  Zoom link:&#160\;https://riceu
	niversity.zoom.us/j/96645631697?pwd=lGlJf4SKugYDNcMDU8COgunoQfq2Mv.1  Meet
	ing ID:&#160\;966 4563 1697Passcode: 061826  (Department : Applied Physics
	)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/events/431544-stochastic-simulations-of-
	radiation-belt\n\nFrom Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/431544-stochastic-simulations-of-ra
	diation-belt
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Herman Brown Hall
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
